"Yes, sir. They must be en route now, we gave them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00 a.m., the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to crush the insurrection. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each returning to their unit, and the sergeants made them mount the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hell Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"Are you talking about the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced toward one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yup, he still has it," replied Cohren as the tank's turret opened with a clank to allow his commander to pass.
"Every tank was en route," declared the commander calmly but clearly from his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to move forward. The Kronos on which Cohren was riding jerked when its brakes were released and it started moving into formation. The tanks spread out in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the swamps and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the beginning of the war, isn't that right?"
"Yup, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we could take them out in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Sundering is a weak word," said Nemic, joining the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we had anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant within the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Christ, we should see it from where we are."
" Well, I'll hold firm for the Federation," said Orson a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"Say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you, eighteen years old, take cover the moment they hear a shot," said Craith.
" I think we'll soon find out," said Cohren laughing. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. Activating the thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Ouep, I see them," replied Cohren via his throat mic.
"Enemy?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to say," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Exodus Company, don't fire unless we fire on you, let them come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures transitioned from blurred spots to more distinct shapes. As they drew closer, one of them ran toward something, seized it, and then dashed back to the small ridge where they were. The figures took positions to fire.
"We have contact," Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from vehicles to take cover behind them. A tank-killer missile whistled past and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew emerged and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 275 meters. 'Fire,' shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air."
"Send the Senti," Knoxx shouted, watching the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened, and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, dashed outside. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Should we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we capture them," Cohren advanced as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ashes and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but ceased quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe among the squad, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked toward the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, commander," answered the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to get rid of this man?"
